Data-based Statistical Decision Model

Lecture 7 supplement - Variable Selection by Lasso

Sungkyu Jung

High-dimensional regression

  • One situation that becomes increasingly common in data science is a high-dimensional regime, where the number of predictors we measure for each data point is bigger than the number of data points, i.e., \(n < p\). The predictors have to be collinear, indeed multicollinear.

  • A very large genetic study might sequence the genes of, say, 500 people — but measure 500,000 genetic markers in each person.

  • If we want to predict some characteristic of the people from the genes (say their height, or blood pressure, or how quickly they would reject a transplanted organ), there is simply no way to estimate a model by ordinary least squares.

  • Any approach to high-dimensional regression must involve either

    • reducing the number of variables, or
    • penalizing the estimates.

Forward stepwise regression

  • For the high-dimensional case (\(p > n\)), we can still fit a linear model with \(q\) variables, as long as \(q < n\).

  • Thus, sequentially adding more variables (i.e. Forward stepwise regression) works for high-dimensional data.

Penalizing the estimates

  • A problem with collinearity is that \({\mathbf X}'{\mathbf X}\) is not invertible.

  • A simple remedy is to inflate the matrix \({\mathbf X}'{\mathbf X}\) by adding \(\lambda {\mathbf I}\), then invert the inflated square matrix \(({\mathbf X}'{\mathbf X}+ \lambda{\mathbf I})\), for some \(\lambda >0\), so that \[\hat\beta_{\lambda} = ({\mathbf X}'{\mathbf X}+ \lambda{\mathbf I})^{-1}{\mathbf X}'{\mathbf Y}.\]

  • This results in “shrinking” the \(\beta\) estimates, and sometimes called a shrinkage estimator.

Shrinkage estimators

we will use the Hitters dataset from the ISLR package to explore two shrinkage methods: ridge regression and lasso. These are otherwise known as penalized regression methods.

We are interested in predicting the players’ salary Salary using all other variables. The predictor variables are offensive and defensive statistics for a number of baseball players. This dataset has some missing data in the response Salary. We use the na.omit() function the clean the dataset.

We use the glmnet() and cv.glmnet() functions from the glmnet package to fit penalized regressions.

library(glmnet)

Unfortunately, the glmnet function does not allow the use of model formulas, so we setup the data for ease of use with glmnet. Alternatively we can use train() from caret which does allow for fitting penalized regression with the formula syntax, but to explore some of the details, we first work with the functions from glmnet directly.

X = model.matrix(Salary ~ ., Hitters)[, -1] # removes the 1 vector for intercept
y = Hitters$Salary

First, we fit an ordinary linear regression, and note the size of the predictors’ coefficients, and predictors’ coefficients squared. (The two penalties we will use.)

fit = lm(Salary ~ ., Hitters)

Ridge Regression

We first illustrate ridge regression, which can be fit using glmnet() with alpha = 0 and seeks to minimize

\[ \sum_{i=1}^{n} \left( y_i - \beta_0 - \sum_{j=1}^{p} \beta_j x_{ij} \right) ^ 2 + \lambda \sum_{j=1}^{p} \beta_j^2 . \]

Notice that the intercept is not penalized.

  • Rewriting the above minimization: \[ ({\mathbf y}- 1_n\beta_0 - {\mathbf X}\beta)'({\mathbf y}- 1_n\beta_0 - {\mathbf X}\beta) + \lambda\beta'\beta\] where \({\mathbf X}\) is the design matrix, except the first column (\(1_n\) vector!), and \(\beta = (\beta_1,\ldots,\beta_p)'\).

  • Solution to the minimization problem is simple, if the data are standardized.

    • If \(\bar{y} = 0\) and \(\bar{x_{i.}} = 0\) for each \(i\), then \(\beta_0 = 0\) and \[\hat\beta_{\lambda} = ({\mathbf X}'{\mathbf X}+ \lambda{\mathbf I})^{-1}{\mathbf X}'{\mathbf Y}.\]

  • The amount of shrinkage of each coefficient depends on the “scale” of \(s_{X_i}^2\).

  • Ridge regression is not scale invariant like the usual unpenalized regression. Thankfully, glmnet() takes care of this internally. It automatically standardizes predictors for fitting, then reports fitted coefficient using the original scale.

The two plots illustrate how much the coefficients are penalized for different values of \(\lambda\). Notice none of the coefficients are forced to be zero.

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
fit_ridge = glmnet(X, y, alpha = 0)
plot(fit_ridge)
plot(fit_ridge, xvar = "lambda", label = TRUE)

Cross-validated choice of \(\lambda\)

  • The plots above suggested that using glmnet() we indeed have computed coefficient estimates for multiple values of \(\lambda\).

  • We use cross-validation to select a good \(\lambda\) value (what do we mean by “good”?). The cv.glmnet()function uses 10 folds by default. The plot illustrates the MSE for the \(\lambda\)s considered. Two lines are drawn.

  • The first is the \(\lambda\) that gives the smallest MSE.

  • The second is the \(\lambda\) that gives an MSE within one standard error of the smallest.

fit_ridge_cv = cv.glmnet(X, y, alpha = 0)
plot(fit_ridge_cv)

One standard error rule

  • Typically, we choose \(\lambda\) with the smallest MSE.

  • This oftentimes leads to a model with a good prediction performance, but a quite complex, less penalized, model. (This becomes obvious when we discuss lasso.)

  • The one standard error rule is an alternative way of choosing \(\lambda\) from the CV curve.

    • We start with the usual estimate \(\hat\lambda = {\mathop{\rm argmin}}_{\lambda} CV(\lambda)\)

    • We move \(lambda\) in the direction of increasing regularization until it ceases to be true that \[CV(\lambda) ≤ CV(\hat\lambda) + SE(\hat\lambda)\]

  • In words, we take the simplest (most regularized) model whose error is within one standard error of the minimal error

The cv.glmnet() function returns several details of the fit for both \(\lambda\) values in the plot. Notice the penalty terms are smaller than the full linear regression. (As we would expect.)

Lasso

  • We now illustrate lasso, which can be fit using glmnet() with alpha = 1 and seeks to minimize

\[ \sum_{i=1}^{n} \left( y_i - \beta_0 - \sum_{j=1}^{p} \beta_j x_{ij} \right) ^ 2 + \lambda \sum_{j=1}^{p} |\beta_j| . \]

  • Like ridge, lasso is not scale invariant.

  • Unlike ridge, there is no simple formula to compute the lasso regression coefficients.

The two plots illustrate how much the coefficients are penalized for different values of \(\lambda\).

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
fit_lasso = glmnet(X, y, alpha = 1)
plot(fit_lasso)
plot(fit_lasso, xvar = "lambda", label = TRUE)

  • Notice some of the coefficients are forced to be zero.

  • Lasso does not only variable shrinkage, but also variable selection!

  • The first plot reflects the fact that the penalized regression for lasso is equivalent to a constrained regression, limiting the size of \(L_1\) norm of \(\beta\). (This, however, is a subject for a higher level course.)

Cross-validated choice of \(\lambda\)

Again, to actually pick a \(\lambda\), we will use cross-validation. The plot is similar to the ridge plot. Notice along the top is the number of features in the model. (Which changed in this plot.)

fit_lasso_cv = cv.glmnet(X, y, alpha = 1)
plot(fit_lasso_cv)

  • Observe the difference in model complexity, from choosing \(\lambda\) by the minimum CV score or by one standard error rule.

cv.glmnet() returns several details of the fit for both \(\lambda\) values in the plot. Notice the penalty terms are again smaller than the full linear regression. (As we would expect.) Some coefficients are 0.

# fitted coefficients, using 1-SE rule lambda, default behavior
coef(fit_lasso_cv)

Tidying the output using broom

Sometimes, the output from glmnet() can be overwhelming. The broom package can help with that.
